In my limited experience, I've found that the hardest part about that brand of writing is that it becomes really difficult to wrap it up in a satisfactory manner. Character flaws are like Kintsugi; they can be beautiful in their own way, but too many and, like kintsugi, they'll call apart at the seams. You can't just handwave away all of their worries, their flaws, and expect them to remain a relatable character afterwards; for example, take Anon in A Marriage of Flesh and Metal. He's done some seriously bad shit in the past, and while he's certainly as level-headed as one can be given the circumstances he was in prior to embarking for the caves of Qud. He means well, and while he can't quite keep his past behind him as well as he'd like to, he still tries his damnedest to do some honest good for the people around him.
